{"title_page": "Ketmen Ridge", "text_new": "{{short description|Mountain range in the Tian Shan system}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}{{more footnotes|date=March 2020}}}}\n\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = '''Ketmen Ridge'''\n| other_name        = \n| etymology         = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| translation       = \n| pronunciation     = \n| photo             = \n| photo_size        = \n| photo_alt         = \n| photo_caption     = \n| map               = \n| map_image         = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n| map_relief        = \n| map_size          = \n| location          = Uygur and Rayimbek districts, Almaty region, Republic of Kazakhstan\n| label             = \n| label_position    = \n| elevation         = \n| elevation_m       = \n| elevation_ft      = \n| elevation_ref     = \n| prominence        = \n| prominence_m      = \n| prominence_ft     = \n| prominence_ref    = \n| isolation         = \n| isolation_km      = \n| isolation_mi      = \n| isolation_ref     = \n| parent_peak       = \n| listing           = \n| range             = \n| coordinates       = \n| coordinates_ref   = \n| topo              = \n| type              = \n| age               = \n| geology           = \n| volcanic_arc      = \n| volcanic_belt     = \n| volcanic_field    = \n| volcanic_arc/belt = \n| last_eruption     = \n| first_ascent      = \n| easiest_route     = \n| normal_route      = \n| access            = \n| child             = \n| embedded          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Ketmen Ridge''' is located south of the [[Trans-Ili Alatau|Zailiyskiy Alatau]] in Northern [[Tian Shan]]. The Ridge is on the territory of the [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] and [[Raiymbek District|Raiymbek]] districts of the [[Almaty Region|Almaty region]] which falls within the [[Republic of Kazakhstan]] and [[China]]. The total length of the Ridge is 310 km, 160 km of which lies in Kazakhstan. The width of the Ridge is about 40\u201350 km. The highest point of the range is Mount Aspan at 3,652 m.[2]\nThe Ridge is adjacent to the K\u00fcng\u00f6y Ala-Too Range in the west and the Narat Ridge in the east. The Northern slopes of the Ridge pass into the Ili Valley. Keen Ridge forms the southern border of Semirechye. \nThe Ridge is composed of igneous and sedimentary rocks, such as effusions, [[granite]], and [[limestone]]. The slopes are steep with gentle peaks below the snow line. The Ridge has a [[permafrost]] zone but does not have glaciation or snowfields. It contains [[steppe]] and [[taiga]] forests, which consist mainly of spruce trees and meadows in high-altitude zones. At the foot of the southern slope of the ridge, steppe bison remains have been found {{citation needed|date=April 2020}}.\n\nThe eponymous Ketmen pass is located at an altitude of 3,040 meters above sea level in the eastern part of the mountain range. A caravan trail from the Ili valley to the Kegen-Tekes hollow is laid through the pass, which connects the Northern slope in the Ketmen gorge and southern slope of the Ridge of the Shalkudysu river valley.\nThe Keen ridge has a wide variety of flora. Research has found that the Ketmen ridge is home to 1890 species of vascular plants, which are angiosperms, dicots, and monocots. Eighty-four species from 11 genera of rust fungi were found. The most abundant genera found were 48 species of Puccinia and 12 species of Uromyces {{citation needed|date=April 2020}}.\n\n== Source and links ==\n* https://www.tripadvisor.com.my/Attraction_Review-g2350619-d15873720-Reviews-Ketmen_Ridge-Almaty_Region.html\n* \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d. \u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 / \u0422. \u041f. \u0424\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 (\u0440\u0435\u0434.). \u2014 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f. \u2014 \u041e\u043c\u0441\u043a: \u041e\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430, 2011. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-9523-0332-4}}\n* \u041a\u0435\u0442\u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0442 // \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d. \u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f. \u2014 \u0410\u043b\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044b: \u049a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u049b \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f\u0441\u044b, 2005. \u2014 \u0422. III. \u2014 {{ISBN|9965-9746-4-0}}.\n* \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 / \u0413\u043b. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041d. \u0410. \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432. \u2014 \u041c. : \u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b, 2012. \u2014 \u0412\u044b\u043f. 227. \u2014 \u0421. 191, 193. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-9551-0634-2}}.\n*Rakhimova YV, Yermekova BD, Kyzmetova LA. (2017). Checklist of rust fungi from Ketmen ridge (southeast of Kazakhstan). Retrieved March 30, 2020 from http://www.plantpathologyquarantine.org/pdf/PPQ_7_2_4.pdf\n\n{{coord missing|Kazakhstan}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Kazakhstan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mountain range in the Tian Shan system}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}{{more footnotes|date=March 2020}}}}\n\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = '''Ketmen Ridge'''\n| other_name        = \n| etymology         = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| translation       = \n| pronunciation     = \n| photo             = \n| photo_size        = \n| photo_alt         = \n| photo_caption     = \n| map               = \n| map_image         = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n| map_relief        = \n| map_size          = \n| location          = Uygur and Rayimbek districts, Almaty region, Republic of Kazakhstan\n| label             = \n| label_position    = \n| elevation         = \n| elevation_m       = \n| elevation_ft      = \n| elevation_ref     = \n| prominence        = \n| prominence_m      = \n| prominence_ft     = \n| prominence_ref    = \n| isolation         = \n| isolation_km      = \n| isolation_mi      = \n| isolation_ref     = \n| parent_peak       = \n| listing           = \n| range             = \n| coordinates       = \n| coordinates_ref   = \n| topo              = \n| type              = \n| age               = \n| geology           = \n| volcanic_arc      = \n| volcanic_belt     = \n| volcanic_field    = \n| volcanic_arc/belt = \n| last_eruption     = \n| first_ascent      = \n| easiest_route     = \n| normal_route      = \n| access            = \n| child             = \n| embedded          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Ketmen Ridge''' is located south of the [[Trans-Ili Alatau|Zailiyskiy Alatau]] in Northern [[Tian Shan]]. The Ridge is on the territory of the [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] and [[Raiymbek District|Raiymbek]] districts of the [[Almaty Region|Almaty region]], falling within the area of the [[Republic of Kazakhstan]] and [[China]]. The total length of the Ridge is 310 km, 160 km of which lies in Kazakhstan. The width of the Ridge is about 40\u201350 km. The highest point of the range is Mount Aspan at 3,652 m.[2]\nThe Ridge is adjacent to the K\u00fcng\u00f6y Ala-Too Range in the west and the Narat Ridge in the east. The Northern slopes of the Ridge pass into the Ili Valley. Keen Ridge forms the southern border of Semirechye. \nThe Ridge is composed of igneous and sedimentary rocks, such as effusions, [[granite]], and [[limestone]]. The slopes are steep with gentle peaks below the snow line. The Ridge has a [[permafrost]] zone but does not have glaciation or snowfields. It contains [[steppe]] and [[taiga]] forests, which consist mainly of spruce trees and meadows in high-altitude zones. At the foot of the southern slope of the ridge, steppe bison remains have been found {{citation needed|date=April 2020}}.\n\nThe eponymous Ketmen pass is located at an altitude of 3,040 meters above sea level in the eastern part of the mountain range. A caravan trail from the Ili valley to the Kegen-Tekes hollow is laid through the pass, which connects the Northern slope in the Ketmen gorge and southern slope of the Ridge of the Shalkudysu river valley.\nThe Keen ridge has a wide variety of flora. Research has found that the Ketmen ridge is home to 1890 species of vascular plants, which are angiosperms, dicots, and monocots. Eighty-four species from 11 genera of rust fungi were found. The most abundant genera found were 48 species of Puccinia and 12 species of Uromyces {{citation needed|date=April 2020}}.\n\n== Source and links ==\n* https://www.tripadvisor.com.my/Attraction_Review-g2350619-d15873720-Reviews-Ketmen_Ridge-Almaty_Region.html\n* \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d. \u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 / \u0422. \u041f. \u0424\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 (\u0440\u0435\u0434.). \u2014 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f. \u2014 \u041e\u043c\u0441\u043a: \u041e\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430, 2011. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-9523-0332-4}}\n* \u041a\u0435\u0442\u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0442 // \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d. \u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f. \u2014 \u0410\u043b\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044b: \u049a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u049b \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f\u0441\u044b, 2005. \u2014 \u0422. III. \u2014 {{ISBN|9965-9746-4-0}}.\n* \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 / \u0413\u043b. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041d. \u0410. \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432. \u2014 \u041c. : \u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b, 2012. \u2014 \u0412\u044b\u043f. 227. \u2014 \u0421. 191, 193. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-9551-0634-2}}.\n*Rakhimova YV, Yermekova BD, Kyzmetova LA. (2017). Checklist of rust fungi from Ketmen ridge (southeast of Kazakhstan). Retrieved March 30, 2020 from http://www.plantpathologyquarantine.org/pdf/PPQ_7_2_4.pdf\n\n{{coord missing|Kazakhstan}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Kazakhstan]]\n", "name_user": "Mmr3b9", "label": "safe", "comment": "Put together a sentence that had a comma and did not flow.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ketmen_Ridge"}
{"title_page": "Ad Astra (Lippold sculpture)", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}{{See also|Ad astra (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Needle at Air and Space Mus. at D.C.jpg\n| painting_alignment =\n| image_size         = 200px\n| title              = Ad Astra\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Richard Lippold\n| year               = {{Start date|1976}}\n| type               = Gold-colored polished stainless steel\n| height_imperial    = 115\n| width_imperial     =\n| length_imperial    =\n| imperial_unit = ft\n| metric_unit = m\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = National Air and Space Museum\n| coordinates        = {{coord|38|53|18.99|N|77|1|11.45|W|region:US}}\n| owner              = [[Smithsonian Institution]]\n}}\n'''''Ad Astra''''' is a public artwork by [[United States|American]] artist [[Richard Lippold]]. The [[abstract art|abstract]] sculpture is located outside on the Jefferson Drive entrance of and in the collection of the [[National Air and Space Museum]].<ref name=\"DCMem\">{{cite web|url=http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0000452.htm |title=Ad Astra sculpture |publisher=Dcmemorials.com |date=2009-04-19 |accessdate=2010-07-29}}</ref><ref name=\"Waymarking\">{{cite web|url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM4A86_Ad_Astra_by_Richard_Lippold_National_Air_and_Space_Museum_Washington_DC |title=\"Ad Astra\" by Richard Lippold |publisher=Waymarking.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-29}}</ref><ref name=\"Smithsonian\">{{cite web|url=http://www.si.edu/Exhibitions/Details/Outdoor-Sculptures-Air-and-Space-Museum-173 |title=Outdoor Sculptures: Air and Space Museum |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |date=6 April 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110429204301/http://www.si.edu/Exhibitions/Details/Outdoor-Sculptures-Air-and-Space-Museum-173| archivedate= 29 April 2011 | url-status= dead}}</ref> The sculpture's title is [[Latin]], meaning [[Ad astra (phrase)|\"To the Stars\"]].<ref name=\"Waymarking\"/>\n\n==Description==\n\nThis abstract statue is made of gold-colored polished [[stainless steel]]. Standing at 100 feet tall, the piece consists of a \"...three-planed narrow shaft ending in a pointed tip, penetrates a triple star-like cluster near its apex\".<ref name=\"inventory\">{{cite web | author=National Air & Space Museum | year=1976 | title=Ad Astra (sculpture) | work=Inventory of American Painting and Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!6510~!0#focus | accessdate= 25 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Oxford\">[https://archive.org/details/oxforddictionary00morg/page/285 <!-- quote=ad astra sculpture washington d.c. --> \"Lippard, Richard\"], ''The Oxford dictionary of American art and artists'', Ann Lee Morgan</ref>\n\n==Information==\n\nLippold believed that \"the characteristic art of our time deals with the conquest of space\", with ''Ad Astra'' symbolizing just that.<ref name=\"Neufeld\">{{cite book |last=Neufeld|first=Michael |author2=Alex Spencer|author3= John Dailey|author4= John Glenn|title=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum: An Autobiography |publisher=[[National Geographic Magazine|National Geographic]]|date=October 2010|isbn=1-4262-0653-4}}</ref><ref name=\"AA1\">{{cite news |title=Ad Astra |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/277538274 |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=Newspapers.com |agency=Star-Gazette |issue=20 June 1976}}</ref> In 2009 the sculpture made an appearance in the film ''[[Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian]]''.<ref name=\"IMDB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3114157/ |title=Richard Lippold |publisher=[[IMDb]] |date= |accessdate=22 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Continuum (sculpture)|''Continuum'' sculpture]]\n* ''[[Delta Solar]]''\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* \"Fabricating a soaring symbol of the space age {Richard Lippold's Ad astra}.\" ''[[AIA Journal]]'' 65, (October 1976): Art Index Retrospective: 1929\u20131984 ([[H. W. Wilson Company]])\n\n==External links==\n* [http://abstractsculpture.wordpress.com/2011/03/01/ad-astra-an-abstract-sculpture-by-richard-lippold/ ''Ad Astra, an Abstract Sculpture by Richard Lippold''] from What is Abstract Sculpture?\n* [http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0000452.htm ''Ad Astra'' on dcMemorials].\n* [http://www.collectos.com/arts/modern-day-medici-wanted-vatican-looks-for-donor-for-richard-lippold-sculpture/ ''Modern-day Medici wanted: Vatican looks for Donor for Richard Lippold Sculpture''] from Collectos.com\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/30/arts/richard-lippold-sculptor-of-metal-abstractions-dies-at-87.html ''Richard Lippold, Sculptor of Metal Abstractions, Dies at 87''] from ''[[The New York Times]]'', a brief mention of the sculpture as a notable work\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1976 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Abstract sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of the Smithsonian Institution]]\n[[Category:Steel sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Southwest Federal Center]]\n\n\n{{Public-art-stub}}\n{{Smithsonian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}{{See also|Ad astra (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Needle at Air and Space Mus. at D.C.jpg\n| painting_alignment =\n| image_size         = 200px\n| title              = Ad Astra\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Richard Lippold\n| year               = {{Start date|1976}}\n| type               = Gold-colored polished stainless steel\n| height_imperial    = 115\n| width_imperial     =\n|